09361nam a22012855i 9780823287512DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232875127 a10.1515/97808232875122doi  a(DE-B1597)555152  a(OCoLC)1178769362  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0700002bisacsh00aCrimmigrant Nations :bResurgent Nationalism and the Closing of Borders /ced. by Robert Koulish, Maartje van der Woude. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The "problem" of migration -- tI. Border criminologies -- t1. Insecurity syndrome: the challenges of trump's carceral state -- t2. Migration, populism, racism: between "old" Italy and "new" Europe -- t3. The promise of the border: immigration control and belonging in contemporary Britain -- tII. Crimmigration under trump -- t4. The terrorism of everyday crime -- t5. The trumping of neoliberal penality? trump's presidency and the rise of nationalist authoritarianism in the united states -- t6. Trump v. Hawaii: trumpeting authoritarianism with formalist analysis and sovereign norms -- t7. A path toward nowhere: the rise of enforcement- based immigration policy -- t8. Trump doesn't tweet dog whistles, he barks with the dogs: crimmigration as a racial project through the lens of trump's twitter -- t9. Mirrors of justice? undocumented immigrants in courts in the united states and Russia -- tIII. Shoring up fortress Europe -- t10. Euroskepticism, nationalism, and the securitization of migration in the Netherlands -- t11. Sorting out welfare: crimmigration practices and abnormal justice in Norway -- t12. The fight against terrorism in Belgium: crimmigration law as a counterterrorism instrument? -- t13. How does crimmigration unfold in Poland? between securitization introduced to polish migration policy by its europeanization and polish xenophobia -- t14. Migration control, citizenship regime, and the spectrum of exclusion in turkey -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the distinction between domestic and international is increasingly blurred along with the line between internal and external borders, migrants-particularly people of color-have become emblematic of the hybrid threat both to national security and sovereignty and to safety and order inside the state. From building walls and fences, overcrowding detention facilities, and beefing up border policing and border controls, a new narrative has arrived that has migrants assume the risk for government-sponsored degradation, misery, and death. Crimmigrant Nations examines the parallel rise of anti-immigrant sentiment and right-wing populism in both the United States and Europe to offer an unprecedented look at this issue on an international level.Beginning with the fears and concerns of immigration that predate the election of Trump, the Brexit vote, and the signing and implementation of the Schengen Agreement, Crimmigrant Nations critically analyzes nationalist state policies in countries that have criminalized migrants and categorized them as threats to national security. Highlighting a pressing and perplexing problem facing the Western world in 2020 and beyond, this collection of essays illustrates not only how anti-immigrant sentiments and nationalist discourse are on the rise in various Western liberal democracies, but also how these sentiments are being translated into punitive and cruel policies and practices that contribute to a merger of crime control and migration control with devastating effects for those falling under its reach. Mapping out how these measures are taken, the rationale behind these policies, and who is subjected to exclusion as a result of these measures, Crimmigrant Nations looks beyond the level of the local or the national to the relational dynamics between different actors on different levels and among different institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh  aBorders.  aCrimmigration.  aImmigration.  aMigration.  aNationalism.  aRace.  aRefugee.  aSocial Control.  aSovereignty.1 aAliverti, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAliverti, Ana.1 aCheliotis, Leonidas K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheliotis, Leonidas.1 aDe Pelecijn, Lana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Pelecijn, Lana.1 aDe Ridder, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Ridder, Steven.1 aDurham, Simone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurham, Simone.1 aGundhus, Helene O.1 aGundhus, Helene O. I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasli, Zeynap.1 aKasli, Zeynep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaus, Witold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaus, Witold.1 aKoulish, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoulish, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKoulish, Robert.1 aKubal, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKubal, Agnieszka.1 aMelossi, Dario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelossi, Dario.1 aOlayo-Méndez, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlayo-Méndez, Alejandro.1 aPlatt, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary